  <section class="service-overview" aria-labelledby="overview-heading">
    <div class="split-intro">
      <div class="split-intro__image" aria-hidden="true">
        <div class="split-intro__image-placeholder">
          <span><em style="font-style:normal;" title="Not yet sourced">[REPRESENTATIVE — NOT YET SOURCED]</em><br />Natural Vermont slate tiles on a historic home<br />Pro Exteriors installation</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="split-intro__copy">
        <span class="eyebrow">A DIFFERENT KIND OF ROOFING DECISION</span>
        <h2 class="section-heading" id="overview-heading">Natural Slate Is Not a 25-Year Roof. It Is a 100-Year Decision.</h2>
        <div class="split-intro__body">
          <p>Natural slate is quarried stone — split along natural cleavage planes to produce tiles that are dense, non-porous, and resistant to the weathering mechanisms that degrade other roofing materials. Hard slate from Vermont and Pennsylvania, correctly installed, has documented lifespans of 100–150 years. Soft slate (from Virginia, Georgia, and international sources) runs 60–125 years depending on the deposit. Either way, a natural slate installation is the last roof most homeowners ever put on a home they intend to keep.</p>
          <p>The trade-offs are real and worth stating directly. Natural slate is the heaviest common roofing material — 14–18 lbs per square foot versus 2–4 lbs for asphalt shingles and 9–12 lbs for clay tile. Not every home's roof framing can support that load without structural reinforcement. The feasibility assessment that opens every Pro Exteriors slate project is not a formality — it determines whether natural slate is viable on your home at all, and if reinforcement is required, what that scope entails before material is ordered.</p>
          <p>If your home can't support natural slate, synthetic slate alternatives — which replicate the appearance at roughly one-quarter the weight — may be a viable option depending on your priority (permanence vs. aesthetics). We'll tell you where you stand at the assessment.</p>
        </div>
        <a
          href="/contact?intent=slate-assessment&source=natural-slate-overview"
          class="btn btn-primary"
          data-event-action="cta-click"
          data-event-label="overview-cta"
          data-event-category="natural-slate"
        >
          Request Your Slate Roof Feasibility Assessment
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

