  <section class="slate-types" aria-labelledby="slate-types-heading">
    <div class="slate-types__header">
      <span class="eyebrow">SLATE VARIETIES</span>
      <h2 class="section-heading" id="slate-types-heading">Hard Slate, Soft Slate, and Synthetic. What Each Option Delivers.</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="slate-types__grid">

      <!-- Hard Slate -->
      <article class="slate-card slate-card--featured">
        <span class="slate-card__badge">125–150 yr</span>
        <div class="slate-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
            <polygon points="3 17 12 3 21 17"/><polyline points="3 17 21 17"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h3>Hard Slate (Vermont / Pennsylvania)</h3>
        <p>The premium natural option — quarried from the dense geological formations of Vermont and Pennsylvania. Hard slate has a documented lifespan of 125–150 years in favorable climates, higher density (greater resistance to impact), and a color range from the deep grays of Unfading Green and Purple-Gray to the classic blue-grays of Bangor Unfading. Higher cost than soft slate; unmatched permanence.</p>
      </article>

      <!-- Soft Slate -->
      <article class="slate-card">
        <span class="slate-card__badge">60–125 yr</span>
        <div class="slate-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
            <rect x="2" y="3" width="20" height="14" rx="2"/><line x1="2" y1="20" x2="22" y2="20"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h3>Soft Slate (Virginia / International)</h3>
        <p>Softer slate from Virginia, Georgia, and international deposits (Spain, Wales) runs 60–125 years depending on the specific deposit and installation conditions. Lower cost than hard Vermont and Pennsylvania slate, with a similar appearance. A viable choice when budget requires compromise between natural slate's permanence and synthetic slate's cost efficiency. Still significantly longer-lived than any other residential roofing material.</p>
      </article>

      <!-- Synthetic Slate -->
      <article class="slate-card">
        <span class="slate-card__badge slate-card__badge--neutral">Structural Fallback</span>
        <div class="slate-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
            <path d="M12 22s8-4 8-10V5l-8-3-8 3v7c0 6 8 10 8 10z"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h3>Synthetic Slate</h3>
        <p>Not natural slate — but worth understanding as an option for homes where the structural load of natural slate is not feasible. Synthetic slate products are manufactured from recycled rubber and plastics, weigh approximately 4–6 lbs per square foot (comparable to asphalt), and replicate natural slate's appearance. Lifespan is typically 40–60 years. Confirm with Pro Exteriors that synthetic slate is available for your project before including this in your scope discussions.</p>
