  <section class="investment-band" aria-labelledby="investment-heading">
    <div class="split-intro split-intro--reverse">
      <div class="split-intro__image" aria-hidden="true">
        <div class="split-intro__image-placeholder">
          <span><em style="font-style:normal;" title="Not yet sourced">[REPRESENTATIVE — NOT YET SOURCED]</em><br />Natural slate close-up<br />Vermont hard slate — Pro Exteriors installation</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="split-intro__copy">
        <span class="eyebrow">THE INVESTMENT</span>
        <h2 class="section-heading" id="investment-heading">Not Cheap. But the Last Roof They'll Ever Need — and the Per-Year Math Proves It.</h2>
        <div class="split-intro__body">
          <p>Natural slate is the most expensive residential roofing material in common use. The material itself costs more than asphalt, tile, or metal. The installation is more labor-intensive and requires specialist crews. The structural work, if needed, adds to the total. There is no version of this that is inexpensive upfront.</p>
          <p>The per-year cost calculation changes the picture. A hard slate installation that costs 4× an asphalt roof but lasts 5× as long has a lower per-year ownership cost before accounting for the two additional tear-offs, disposal costs, and re-installations an asphalt timeline requires over 125 years. And slate doesn't degrade over time the way asphalt does — a 100-year-old Vermont slate roof isn't "almost used up." It's middle-aged.</p>
          <p>Financing is available for qualified projects. For homeowners who want the permanence story without the slate price point, the <a href="/residential/tile-clay-roofing" style="color: var(--color-accent); text-decoration: underline;">clay and tile roofing</a> page covers the next tier down. For a full comparison of material options, see <a href="/residential/roof-replacement" style="color: var(--color-accent); text-decoration: underline;">roof replacement</a>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- =========================================================
       FAQ
       STRUCTURAL GATE PLACEMENT 3 of 3 (FAQ answer 2)
  ========================================================= -->
  <section class="faq" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="faq__header">
      <span class="eyebrow">FREQUENTLY ASKED</span>
      <h2 class="section-heading" id="faq-heading">Natural Slate Roofing Questions, Answered.</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="faq__list">

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3 class="faq-item__q">Is natural slate the most expensive roofing material?</h3>
        <div class="faq-item__a">
          <p>Yes, among commonly installed residential roofing materials, natural slate is at the top of the cost range. Material costs are higher than asphalt, metal, or clay tile. Installation requires specialist labor and takes longer. Structural reinforcement, if needed, adds to the total project cost.</p>
          <p>The per-year cost comparison tells a different story. Hard slate from Vermont or Pennsylvania has documented 125–150 year lifespans. An asphalt shingle replacement cycle runs 25–30 years. Over 125 years, a slate installation eliminates four complete roof replacement cycles — plus the associated tear-off costs, dump fees, and disruption of each replacement. For homeowners planning to hold a property long-term, the economics of slate become defensible at the whole-project level. For homeowners planning to sell in the near term, it does not pencil.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3 class="faq-item__q">How do I know if my home can support slate?</h3>
        <div class="faq-item__a">
          <p>You need a structural assessment from a contractor trained on slate load requirements — which is step one of every Pro Exteriors natural slate project. Natural slate runs 14–18 lbs per square foot. The key structural variables are rafter size, rafter span, and the current condition of the roof decking. Homes built for asphalt shingles (framed for 2–4 lbs per square foot) may require rafter reinforcement, additional decking support, or re-framing of specific spans to handle the load.</p>
          <p>Some homes are straightforward candidates. Some require modest reinforcement. Some are not viable for natural slate under any reasonable investment threshold — and in those cases, synthetic slate (at 4–6 lbs per square foot) may be an alternative if the aesthetic is the priority. We tell you which category you're in at the assessment, not after material is sourced.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3 class="faq-item__q">Can slate roofing be repaired, or does it have to be fully replaced?</h3>
        <div class="faq-item__a">
          <p>Individual slate tiles can be replaced without replacing the full roof — this is one of slate's practical advantages. If a tile is cracked or broken from impact or settling, a qualified slate installer can remove the damaged tile and set a new one without disturbing the surrounding slates.</p>
          <p>The limiting factor is matching the original slate material. Vermont hard slate has a specific color, texture, and thickness. If your existing roof used a distinctive slate variety, sourcing matching replacement tiles can require some lead time or specialist sourcing. Pro Exteriors maintains supplier relationships with quarries and slate distributors for exactly this reason.</p>
          <p>Full replacement becomes the right call when the slate has reached the end of its service life (soft slate that has begun to spall and delaminate), when the original installation was done incorrectly (improper fasteners, inadequate underlayment), or when a re-roofing project requires structural modification that makes a full tear-off necessary.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3 class="faq-item__q">Is slate roofing available in my area?</h3>
        <div class="faq-item__a">
          <p>Pro Exteriors installs natural slate roofing across Texas, Colorado, Kansas, Missouri, and Georgia. Availability in your specific area depends on whether your project scope and property type make slate a viable installation — which the structural assessment determines. We do not limit slate work to specific metro areas within our served states; the constraint is structural feasibility and project scope, not geography.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

